March 15th
33
Dearest Debs;
I
am really getting very fond
of this
little old typewriter,
it is
easier for
me to write
on it than by hand because as you know my arm is
still
not
so good
that
is it hurts me a little to
write
at much length.
So I hope you dont mind
this.
I have just this minute received
your
6th and 7th letters
together with
one
from Bo.
What
delayed them since yesterday
I do not know.
Want to
take this opportunity to answer
some
questions
in
yours of the 14th.
The ST.L.G.8Q
are
running true to
form I fear.
Hope
you will
have ben able to get that
account straightened
out by
this time.
Also hope that
Mary Love will
be able
to get McCurdy
to pay the bill
for water bur agree
with you that
we
ahould not coll-
ect under the lease if it will jeopardise the lease.
The important thing now is to keep the house rented.
I have not heard yet about the sale of the two acres
actually being completed and
payment received. Hope
Ralph was able to handle that for us.
Poor Henry he has a real
problem with
Kitty. As you say she is just plain poison, and is
getting worse all the time.
The Income tax matter is
OK. I should have told you about that but it was one
of the things I failed to do. The Treasury Dept. was
trying to take advantage of a technicality to cheat
me out
of # 2,000.00 and I think that by filing an
ammended return I
will ultimately be able to get some
money back which I have already paid. Your Father's
auditor fixed up the ammended return for me and it is
just possible that he may be able to represent my int-
ersts without waiting until 1934. You might send this
letter, or this part of it to your Father with a re-
port of what Aud's lawyer wrote for you to the author-
ities in Washington. X&
Regarding
Ralph's assignment to our children
I wish you would write to the ST.L Union and tell them
that you know I do not want that done.
Lots 7 lots of hoir. Bus
